                45,
                689,
                301,
                718
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "<sup>1</sup>Just for reference a better way to analyze this is through arithmetic intensity proposed by Sammuel Williams [41] which will be discussed in Sec.II-A.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "<sup>1</sup>Just for reference a better way to analyze this is through arithmetic intensity proposed by Sammuel Williams [41] which will be discussed in Sec.II-A.",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    689,
                    301,
                    718
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 0,
              "bbox": [
                305,
                144,
                563,
                275
              ],
              "type": "image",
              "text": "",
              "line_count": 0,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": []
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 0,
              "bbox": [
                307,
                365,
                564,
                498
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "or needs to be fetched from DRAM. With this assumption, even if 80\\% of data is readily available in cache, and only 20\\% needs to be fetched from DRAM, the time to complete the operation will be completely limited by DRAM if it takes more than 5 cycles to fetch the 20\\% cache-miss data from it. This means that no matter how fast the hardware could perform arithmetics per second, the problem will be entirely limited by DRAM bandwidth. They predicted that the diverging speed of improvement of how fast computations can be performed versus how fast data can be fetched is going to create a \"memory wall\" issue [25, 42]. Based on this they concluded:",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "or needs to be fetched from DRAM. With this assumption, even if ",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    365,
                    564,
                    498
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "80\\%",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    365,
                    564,
                    498
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " of data is readily available in cache, and only ",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    365,
                    564,
                    498
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "20\\%",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    365,
                    564,
                    498
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " needs to be fetched from DRAM, the time to complete the operation will be completely limited by DRAM if it takes more than 5 cycles to fetch the ",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    365,
                    564,
                    498
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "20\\%",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    365,
                    564,
                    498
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " cache-miss data from it. This means that no matter how fast the hardware could perform arithmetics per second, the problem will be entirely limited by DRAM bandwidth. They predicted that the diverging speed of improvement of how fast computations can be performed versus how fast data can be fetched is going to create a \"memory wall\" issue [25, 42]. Based on this they concluded:",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    365,
                    564,
                    498
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 0,
              "bbox": [
                318,
                519,
                555,
                569
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "\"Each is improving exponentially, but the exponent for microprocessors is substantially larger than that for DRAMs. The difference between diverging exponentials also grows exponentially.\"",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Each is improving exponentially, but the exponent for microprocessors is substantially larger than that for DRAMs. The difference between diverging exponentials also grows exponentially.\"",
                  "bbox": [
                    318,
                    519,
                    555,
                    569
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 0,
              "bbox": [
                308,
                584,
                563,
                608
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Several later works also reported a similar observation [12, 24, 25, 31, 36, 40].",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "Several later works also reported a similar observation [12, 24, 25, 31, 36, 40].",
                  "bbox": [
                    308,
                    584,
                    563,
                    608
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 0,
              "bbox": [
                307,
                609,
                564,
                705
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "In this work, we re-examined this trend by studying more recent data, with a particular focus on hardware used to train AI models, as well as the characteristics of the computations used for training/serving them. 30 years after, the above observations and predictions could not be further correct. Despite many innovations in memory technology, the trend shows that the \"memory wall\" is increasingly becoming the dominant bottleneck for a range of AI tasks.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "In this work, we re-examined this trend by studying more recent data, with a particular focus on hardware used to train AI models, as well as the characteristics of the computations used for training/serving them. 30 years after, the above observations and predictions could not be further correct. Despite many innovations in memory technology, the trend shows that the \"memory wall\" is increasingly becoming the dominant bottleneck for a range of AI tasks.",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    609,
                    564,
                    705
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 0,
              "bbox": [
                318,
                707,
                564,
                719
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "We first start by analyzing how peak compute of server",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "We first start by analyzing how peak compute of server",
                  "bbox": [
                    318,
                    707,
                    564,
                    719
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                47,
                48,
                303,
                179
              ],
              "type": "image",
              "text": "",
              "line_count": 0,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": []
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                308,
                48,
                563,
                180
              ],
              "type": "image",
              "text": "",
              "line_count": 0,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": []
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                314,
                301,
                373
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "grade AI hardware has changed since 1998 when Yann Lecun trained the famous Lenet-5 model on MNIST data [22]. We can see that the peak compute of the hardware has increased by 60,000 \\times over the past 20 years, as opposed to a 100 \\times increase for DRAM or a 30 \\times increase for interconnect bandwidth.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "grade AI hardware has changed since 1998 when Yann Lecun trained the famous Lenet-5 model on MNIST data [22]. We can see that the peak compute of the hardware has increased by ",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    314,
                    301,
                    373
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "60,000 \\times",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    314,
                    301,
                    373
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " over the past 20 years, as opposed to a ",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    314,
                    301,
                    373
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "100 \\times",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    314,
                    301,
                    373
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " increase for DRAM or a ",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    314,
                    301,
                    373
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "30 \\times",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    314,
                    301,
                    373
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " increase for interconnect bandwidth.",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    314,
                    301,
                    373
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                373,
                301,
                481
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The memory wall problem involves both the limited capacity, the bandwidth of memory transfer, as well as its latency (which has been even harder to improve [32] than bandwidth). This entails different levels of memory data transfer. For example, data transfer between compute logic and on-chip memory, or between compute logic and DRAM memory, or across different processors on different sockets. In all these cases, the capacity and the speed of data transfer has been significantly lagging behind hardware compute capabilities.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "The memory wall problem involves both the limited capacity, the bandwidth of memory transfer, as well as its latency (which has been even harder to improve [32] than bandwidth). This entails different levels of memory data transfer. For example, data transfer between compute logic and on-chip memory, or between compute logic and DRAM memory, or across different processors on different sockets. In all these cases, the capacity and the speed of data transfer has been significantly lagging behind hardware compute capabilities.",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    373,
                    301,
                    481
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                481,
                301,
                589
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Now, if we study the trend of recent AI models, and in particular LLMs, we notice that practitioners, motivated by neural scaling law [14], have been scaling the amount of data, model size, and compute needed to train recent models at unprecedented levels. Even though compute / floating-point operations (FLOPs)^3 needed to train these recent models has increased by a factor of 750 \\times 2\\mathrm{yrs} in the 2018-2022 time frame (see Figure 2), compute is not necessarily the bottleneck, especially for model serving.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "Now, if we study the trend of recent AI models, and in particular LLMs, we notice that practitioners, motivated by neural scaling law [14], have been scaling the amount of data, model size, and compute needed to train recent models at unprecedented levels. Even though compute / floating-point operations (FLOPs)",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    481,
                    301,
                    589
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "^3",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    481,
                    301,
                    589
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " needed to train these recent models has increased by a factor of ",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    481,
                    301,
                    589
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "750 \\times 2\\mathrm{yrs}",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    481,
                    301,
                    589
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " in the 2018-2022 time frame (see Figure 2), compute is not necessarily the bottleneck, especially for model serving.",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    481,
                    301,
                    589
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                589,
                301,
                673
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "First, the LLM sizes have scaled at a rate of 410 \\times 2\\mathrm{yrs} in that time frame, exceeding memory available on single chip. One might hope that we can use distributed-memory parallelism by scaling-out the training/serving to multiple accelerators to avoid the single hardware's limited memory capacity and bandwidth. However, distributing the work over multiple processes can also face the memory wall problem:",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "First, the LLM sizes have scaled at a rate of ",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    589,
                    301,
                    673
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "410 \\times 2\\mathrm{yrs}",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    589,
                    301,
                    673
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " in that time frame, exceeding memory available on single chip. One might hope that we can use distributed-memory parallelism by scaling-out the training/serving to multiple accelerators to avoid the single hardware's limited memory capacity and bandwidth. However, distributing the work over multiple processes can also face the memory wall problem:",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    589,
                    301,
                    673
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                681,
                301,
                719
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "3Please note that we use FLOPs with lowercase s to denote the number of floating point operations needed to perform a task, and FLOPS with capital S to denote the rate at which a given hardware can perform floating point operations per second.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "3Please note that we use FLOPs with lowercase s to denote the number of floating point operations needed to perform a task, and FLOPS with capital S to denote the rate at which a given hardware can perform floating point operations per second.",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    681,
                    301,
                    719
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                307,
                314,
                564,
                373
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "the communication bottleneck of moving data between neural network (NN) accelerators, which is even slower and less efficient than on-chip data movement. Similar to the single system memory case, we have not been able to overcome the technological challenges to scale the network bandwidth.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "the communication bottleneck of moving data between neural network (NN) accelerators, which is even slower and less efficient than on-chip data movement. Similar to the single system memory case, we have not been able to overcome the technological challenges to scale the network bandwidth.",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    314,
                    564,
                    373
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                307,
                376,
                564,
                484
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Second, even when the model fits within a single chip, intra-chip memory transfers from/to registers, L2 cache, global memory, etc. are still increasingly becoming the bottleneck. Thanks to the recent advancements in specialized compute units, such as Tensor cores, the arithmetic operations for a large set of computations can finish in a few cycles. Therefore, to keep these arithmetic units utilized at all times one needs to rapidly feed them large amounts of data, and that is where the chip memory bandwidth becomes the bottleneck.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "Second, even when the model fits within a single chip, intra-chip memory transfers from/to registers, L2 cache, global memory, etc. are still increasingly becoming the bottleneck. Thanks to the recent advancements in specialized compute units, such as Tensor cores, the arithmetic operations for a large set of computations can finish in a few cycles. Therefore, to keep these arithmetic units utilized at all times one needs to rapidly feed them large amounts of data, and that is where the chip memory bandwidth becomes the bottleneck.",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    376,
                    564,
                    484
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                307,
                487,
                564,
                571
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "As one can see in Figure 1, over the past 20 years, peak server hardware FLOPS has been scaling at 3.0 \\times / 2 yrs, outpacing the growth of DRAM and interconnect bandwidth, which have only scaled at 1.6 and 1.4 times every 2 years, respectively. This disparity has made memory, rather than compute, increasingly become a bottleneck, even for cases when the model can fit within a single chip.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "As one can see in Figure 1, over the past 20 years, peak server hardware FLOPS has been scaling at ",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    487,
                    564,
                    571
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "3.0 \\times / 2",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    487,
                    564,
                    571
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": " yrs, outpacing the growth of DRAM and interconnect bandwidth, which have only scaled at 1.6 and 1.4 times every 2 years, respectively. This disparity has made memory, rather than compute, increasingly become a bottleneck, even for cases when the model can fit within a single chip.",
                  "bbox": [
                    307,
                    487,
                    564,
                    571
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                308,
                573,
                564,
                622
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Next, we perform a detailed case study for Transformers which helps better showcase the interplay between FLOPs, Memory Operations (MOPs), and end-to-end runtime by considering common models used today.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "Next, we perform a detailed case study for Transformers which helps better showcase the interplay between FLOPs, Memory Operations (MOPs), and end-to-end runtime by considering common models used today.",
                  "bbox": [
                    308,
                    573,
                    564,
                    622
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 1,
              "bbox": [
                308,
                645,
                564,
                719
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "<sup>3</sup>We are specifically not including the cost of training reinforcement learning models in this figure, as the training cost is mostly related to the simulation environment, and there is currently no consensus on a standard simulation environment. Also note that we report the PFLOPs required to train each model to avoid using any approximation for hardware deployment utilization, as the latter depends on the specific library and the hardware used. Finally, all the rates in this document have been computed by solving a linear regression to fit the data shown in each graph.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "<sup>3</sup>We are specifically not including the cost of training reinforcement learning models in this figure, as the training cost is mostly related to the simulation environment, and there is currently no consensus on a standard simulation environment. Also note that we report the PFLOPs required to train each model to avoid using any approximation for hardware deployment utilization, as the latter depends on the specific library and the hardware used. Finally, all the rates in this document have been computed by solving a linear regression to fit the data shown in each graph.",
                  "bbox": [
                    308,
                    645,
                    564,
                    719
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 2,
              "bbox": [
                136,
                49,
                211,
                60
              ],
              "type": "title",
              "text": "II. CASE STUDY",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "II. CASE STUDY",
                  "bbox": [
                    136,
                    49,
                    211,
                    60
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 2,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                68,
                301,
                153
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "In this section, we first outline the run-time characteristics and the performance bottleneck associated with Transformer inference. We examine two different variations of the Transformer architecture: the encoder architecture (e.g., BERT [7]), which concurrently processes all tokens, and the decoder architecture (e.g., GPT [3, 33]), which runs auto-regressively to process and generate one token at each iteration.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "In this section, we first outline the run-time characteristics and the performance bottleneck associated with Transformer inference. We examine two different variations of the Transformer architecture: the encoder architecture (e.g., BERT [7]), which concurrently processes all tokens, and the decoder architecture (e.g., GPT [3, 33]), which runs auto-regressively to process and generate one token at each iteration.",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    68,
                    301,
                    153
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 2,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                166,
                146,
                178
              ],
              "type": "title",
              "text": "A. Arithmetic Intensity",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "A. Arithmetic Intensity",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    166,
                    146,
                    178
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 2,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                182,
                301,
                303
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "A popular method for measuring performance bottlenecks is to compute the total number of FLOPs required to compute the Transformer encoder-only and decoder-only models. However, this metric in isolation can be very misleading. Instead, one needs to study the arithmetic intensity of the operations involved. Arithmetic intensity is the number of FLOPs that can be performed per byte loaded from memory. It can be computed by dividing the total number of FLOPs by the total number of bytes accessed (also referred to as MOPs, or memory operations) [41]^{4}:",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "A popular method for measuring performance bottlenecks is to compute the total number of FLOPs required to compute the Transformer encoder-only and decoder-only models. However, this metric in isolation can be very misleading. Instead, one needs to study the arithmetic intensity of the operations involved. Arithmetic intensity is the number of FLOPs that can be performed per byte loaded from memory. It can be computed by dividing the total number of FLOPs by the total number of bytes accessed (also referred to as MOPs, or memory operations) [41]",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    182,
                    301,
                    303
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "^{4}",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    182,
                    301,
                    303
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": ":",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    182,
                    301,
                    303
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 2,
              "bbox": [
                102,
                309,
                301,
                334
              ],
              "type": "interline_equation",
              "text": "\\text {A r i t h m e t i c I n t e n s i t y} = \\frac {\\# \\mathrm {F L O P s}}{\\# \\mathrm {M O P s}}. \\tag {1}",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "\\text {A r i t h m e t i c I n t e n s i t y} = \\frac {\\# \\mathrm {F L O P s}}{\\# \\mathrm {M O P s}}. \\tag {1}",
                  "bbox": [
                    102,
                    309,
                    301,
                    334
                  ],
                  "type": "interline_equation"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 2,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                340,
                301,
                413
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "To illustrate the importance of considering Arithmetic Intensity, we studied BERT-Base and BERT-Large [7], along with GPT-2 [33]. The first two are encoder models, which involve matrix-matrix operations for their inference, and the latter is a decoder/auto-regressive model, where its inference involves repeated matrix-vector multiplications.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "To illustrate the importance of considering Arithmetic Intensity, we studied BERT-Base and BERT-Large [7], along with GPT-2 [33]. The first two are encoder models, which involve matrix-matrix operations for their inference, and the latter is a decoder/auto-regressive model, where its inference involves repeated matrix-vector multiplications.",
                  "bbox": [
                    45,
                    340,
                    301,
                    413
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
