            {
              "page_idx": 4,
              "bbox": [
                308,
                670,
                564,
                719
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The computational cost of training recent SOTA Transformer models in NLP has been scaling at a rate of 750 \\times /2\\mathrm{yrs}, and the model parameter size has been scaling at 410 \\times /2\\mathrm{yrs}. In contrast, the peak hardware FLOPS has been scaling at",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "The computational cost of training recent SOTA Transformer models in NLP has been scaling at a rate of ",
                  "bbox": [
                    308,
                    670,
                    564,
                    719
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "750 \\times /2\\mathrm{yrs}",
                  "bbox": [
                    308,
                    670,
                    564,
                    719
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": ", and the model parameter size has been scaling at ",
                  "bbox": [
                    308,
                    670,
                    564,
                    719
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                },
                {
                  "text": "410 \\times /2\\mathrm{yrs}",
                  "bbox": [
                    308,
                    670,
                    564,
                    719
                  ],
                  "type": "inline_equation"
                },
                {
                  "text": ". In contrast, the peak hardware FLOPS has been scaling at",
                  "bbox": [
                    308,
                    670,
                    564,
                    719
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 5,
              "bbox": [
                45,
                49,
                301,
                193
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "a rate of 3.0 \\times / 2\\mathrm{yrs}, while both the DRAM and interconnect bandwidth have been increasingly falling behind, with a scaling rate of 1.6 \\times / 2\\mathrm{yrs} and 1.4 \\times / 2\\mathrm{yrs}, respectively. To put these numbers into perspective, peak hardware FLOPS has increased by 60,000 \\times over the past 20 years, while DRAM/Interconnect bandwidth has only scaled by a factor of 100 \\times / 30 \\times over the same time period, respectively. With these trends, memory — in particular, intra/inter-chip memory transfer — will soon become the main limiting factoring in serving large AI models. As such, we need to rethink the training, deployment, and design of AI models as well as how we design AI hardware to deal with this increasingly challenging memory wall.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                612,
                792
              ],
              "spans": [
