            {
              "page_idx": 7,
              "bbox": [
                39,
                430,
                292,
                491
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The original design of the rectangular DNA origami structure shown in Supplementary Figure 1 was established by Rothemund<sup>16</sup>. This design was used as the blank template in this work and functional strands were used to replace the original strands at the corresponding positions. The position and sequences of the functional staple strands are shown in different colors in Supplementary Figures 1-3 and Supplementary Note 1.",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                594,
                783
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "The original design of the rectangular DNA origami structure shown in Supplementary Figure 1 was established by Rothemund<sup>16</sup>. This design was used as the blank template in this work and functional strands were used to replace the original strands at the corresponding positions. The position and sequences of the functional staple strands are shown in different colors in Supplementary Figures 1-3 and Supplementary Note 1.",
                  "bbox": [
                    39,
                    430,
                    292,
                    491
                  ],
                  "type": "text"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "page_idx": 7,
              "bbox": [
                39,
                500,
                292,
                610
              ],
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Rectangular DNA nanosheets. Rectangular DNA nanostructures were made by mixing a long single-stranded scaffold strand (7249 DNA derived from M13 bacteriophage) with short strands (including staple strands and functional strands) in 1 \\times TAE-Mg buffer (40~\\mathrm{mM} Tris, 20~\\mathrm{mM} acetic acid, pH 8.0, 2~\\mathrm{mM} EDTA, 12.5~\\mathrm{mM}\\mathrm{Mg}(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\mathrm{COOH})_2). The final concentrations of scaffold DNA and basic staple strands were 10~\\mathrm{nM} and 80~\\mathrm{nM}, respectively. The mixture was heated to 65^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}, then annealed by cooling to 25^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C} at a rate of 10\\mathrm{min} / {}^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C} using an Eppendorf thermal cycler (Eppendorf Mastercycler ep Gradient S, Hamburg, Germany). Unless otherwise stated, all DNA strands or aptamers were purchased from the oligonucleotide synthesis service of Invitrogen (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, CA).",
              "line_count": 1,
              "page_size": [
                594,
                783
              ],
              "spans": [
                {
                  "text": "Rectangular DNA nanosheets. Rectangular DNA nanostructures were made by mixing a long single-stranded scaffold strand (7249 DNA derived from M13 bacteriophage) with short strands (including staple strands and functional strands) in ",
